NFS issue:

To check the NFS mounts, view fstab file : cat /etc/fstab

lahehrlst02:/sapmnt/HST/profile         /sapmnt/HST/profile     nfs vers=3,rw,soft,intr      1 2
lahehrlst02:/sapmnt/HST/global          /sapmnt/HST/global      nfs  vers=3,rw,soft,intr     1 2

The above data will be present on the fstab file, lahehrlst02:/sapmnt/HST/global -- source from where the data is coming, remote server, nfs server
/sapmnt/HST/global -- the mount point present on our local server, nfs client.

systemctl status nfs-server -- to check if the nfs service working properly.
then
systemctl restart nfs-server -- if issue found.

if not go the server which is exporting:

check if the nfs services are running, if not restart.
check : cat /etc/exports

and now come to local server:

DO:

umount -l /sapmnt/HST/profile -- lazy mount the FS having the issue.

then
if needed : systemctl restart nfs-server
and then at last :

mount -t nfs -o nfsvers=3 lahehrlst02:/sapmnt/HST/global /sapmnt/HST/global

mount -a --> this reads the fstab file and it does what ever is written in it.
lsblk -f -- to get the UUID of the device/disk to mount to the device.
ls -lZ -- to know the SElinux, format

